What is CTE
A Common Table Expression is a temporary named result set that is defined using ‘with’. 

Why CTE
CTEs simplify complex queries, make them easier to read, and can be reused multiple times within the same query.

1. Which customers have rented more than 5 movies

WITH RentalCount AS (SELECT customer_id, 
                     COUNT(*) AS total_rentals
                     FROM rental
                     GROUP BY customer_id)
SELECT *
FROM RentalCount
WHERE total_rentals > 5;

2. Which Filmas are longer than the average film length

WITH avg_length AS (
    SELECT AVG(length) AS average_length
    FROM film
)
SELECT title, length
FROM film
WHERE length > (
    SELECT average_length
    FROM avg_length
);

3. staff members who processed more than 300 payments

WITH staff_payment_count AS (
    SELECT staff_id, COUNT(*) AS total_payments
    FROM payment
    GROUP BY staff_id
)
SELECT first_name, last_name
FROM staff
WHERE staff_id IN (
    SELECT staff_id
    FROM staff_payment_count
    WHERE total_payments > 300
);

4. Films with replacement cost higher than average

WITH avg_replacement AS (
    SELECT AVG(replacement_cost) AS avg_cost
    FROM film
)
SELECT title, replacement_cost
FROM film
WHERE replacement_cost > (
    SELECT avg_cost
    FROM avg_replacement
);

5. Customers who paid more than 100 in total

WITH customer_total_payment AS (
    SELECT customer_id, SUM(amount) AS total_amount
    FROM payment
    GROUP BY customer_id
)
SELECT first_name, last_name
FROM customer
WHERE customer_id IN (
    SELECT customer_id
    FROM customer_total_payment
    WHERE total_amount > 100
);

What is Recursive CTE
It is a Query that keeps running itself to get data step-by-step.

Why Recursive CTE
It handle self-referencing data where the number of levels is unknown, allowing query to repeatedly process data until all levels are retrieved.

How it works
It has 2 parts:  Anchor member -> It is a starting point, Recursive member -> repeats the process.


Limitations of CTEs
A CTE works only while the query runs, then it disappears.
Performance of CTEs can be slowed if reused many times.
Some databases limit using CTEs with INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE.

Diff b/w CTE & Subquery
CTE: Can be used multiple times, improves readability for complex queries, works efficiently when used multiple times.
Subquery: Typically used once, can become difficult to read when nested, not as efficient if repeated multiple times.

Temporary tables
It is created to store data for a short time, usually during a query, and it gets removed automatically.

Why Temporary Table
Store results and reuse them later in the query.

1. List all films whose rental rate is higher than the average rental rate of all films.

CREATE TEMPORARY TABLE avg_rental_rate AS
SELECT AVG(rental_rate) AS avg_rate
FROM film;

SELECT *
FROM film
WHERE rental_rate > (
    SELECT avg_rate
    FROM avg_rental_rate
);

What is View
It is a saved query that can be reused later.

Adv of View
1.	Increase scope to database level.
2.	Restricting the users i.e, Abstraction
3.	Instead of pre storing the data its going to execute to bring the data

1. Show all films with rental rate is 0.99

 CREATE VIEW cheap_films AS
SELECT title, rental_rate
FROM film
WHERE rental_rate = 0.99;
SELECT * FROM cheap_films;
